<Base title="About — Acme Coffee Roasters">
  <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
  <h1>Two roasters, one drum.</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Acme started in 2018 in a converted bakery garage. The drum roaster came
    from an auction in Des Moines. The name came from a kid's lunchbox.
  </p>

  <h2>What we believe about roast</h2>
  <p>
    We don't roast past medium. Light-to-medium holds more of what the farm did
    — the acidity, the fruit, the character you paid for. If you want a French
    roast, there are plenty of shops in town that'll do that better than we
    will.
  </p>
  <p>
    Every lot gets cupped before we release it. If a bag isn't what we thought
    it'd be, it goes back or gets blended. We'd rather short a week than send
    something we don't stand behind.
  </p>

  <h2>Who's here</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Dana</strong> runs the roaster and the books.
    <strong>Mike</strong> runs the bar and the wholesale accounts.
    Saturdays you'll usually see both of us.
  </p>

  <h2>Where we buy from</h2>
  <p>
    We buy green coffee through two importers — one in Oakland, one in
    Brooklyn. Whenever we can trace a lot back to a named farm or cooperative,
    we put that on the bag. Some weeks that's most of what we have; some weeks
    it's none of it. We'll tell you when it's which.
  </p>
</Base>
